   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1243_1816_06_11_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">EdgeworthsTown</placeName> <date when="1816-06-11"/>June 11<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 16<lb/></dateline>  

               <salute>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName></salute></opener>

               I trust you will not</lb>
               think my interference</lb>
               troublesome but I cannot help saying that for</lb>
               your sake and for William &amp; the public's I wish</lb>
               that your letter to M[superscript]r[/superscript]. Croker were published-</lb>
               and I request you will tell me whether [deletion]suppos[/deletion]</lb>
               [deletion]ing Mr Croker[/deletion] you would have any objection to</lb>
               it being published if M[superscript]r.[/superscript] Croker wished it as much</lb>
               as I do- Maria Edgeworth</lb>

            
            <p>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName></lb>
                 I am glad that I have received the copy</lb>
              of your letter to M[superscript]r[/superscript] Croker, before my fathers</lb>
              return home, that I might have it in my</lb>
              power to write to you, before I hear the opinions</lb>
              of the higher Powers. I must [insertion]say[/insertion] if you will</lb>
              allow of your [unclear]servants[/unclear] praise, that I think the</lb>
              letter most clear, modest, yet manly and dis-</lb>
              interested. And the arguments, for combining</lb>
              the Coast with the interior survey of this kingdom,</lb>
              unanswerable. And much as it thwarts my</lb>
              interest or rather my ambition, yet I must ac-</lb>
              -knowledge that the military surveyors, are the</lb>
              proper body to be employed.</lb>
              However, I think if it was suggested to,[unclear]Mudge[/unclear]</lb>
            
          
          that two active companies might be formed</lb>
              out of the present body, now employed in</lb>
              Scotland, that he or rather government, would</lb>
              catch eagerly at the idea, for all they want</lb>
              are situations in which they can place the un-</lb>
              employed officers, without the appearance of</lb>
              jobbing. And it is clear that an accurate</lb>
              Survey of Ireland, is called for on all sides</lb>
              By the Admiralty, the military and by</lb>
              the new grand Jury bill.</lb>
              As to instruments the expense of an entire</lb>
              new set is a trifle compared to the expense</lb>
              of the whole work, And in the next theodolite</lb>
              they will improve upon the last.</lb>
              No time need be lost, for I am sure they have</lb>
              instruments sufficient, for selecting their stations</lb>
              and laying out the ground for their [underline]base[/underline]</lb>
              [underline]lines[/underline]. It is wonderful since Gen. Roy's time</lb>
              and with all the experience that they have had,</lb>
              if two men are not to be found under Mudge</lb>
              Who are capable of carrying on separately, a</lb>
              distinct survey. The [unclear]cumulation[/unclear] that will</lb>
              
              necessarily be exited will be advantageous to</lb>
              both companies, and to the survey of the two</lb>
              countries. Then we shall have a chance of their</lb>
              attempting some improvements.</lb>
              The Ed. review will drive them to something new</lb>
              in the Scotch mountains. I do not in this plan</lb>
              look forward to being employed under this new</lb>
              Corps, because without I was well paid it would</lb>
              lead me entirely into one branch of my profession</lb>
              This is what you said originally about my [deletion]being[/deletion]</lb>
              employment with you. And now I must</lb>
              tell you that I am as little disappointed as</lb>
              the [unclear][/unclear] of a [underline]philosopher[/underline] and not of a [underline]Genius[/underline]</lb>
              ought to be. And the chief cause of any sorrow</lb>
              that I may feel, is from my not being likely to</lb>
              see you, busy in Ireland. I fear that I</lb>
              shall be long enough tied here, from various</lb>
              disappointments, Roscommon [insertion]maps[/insertion] can not be finished</lb>
              for two years more. Most fortunately the three</lb>
              months that you [insertion]so promptly[/insertion] allowed me, induced Major Taylor</lb>
              to have my name put in the Engineers warrant</lb>
              from the Post Masters General, for laying out two</lb>
              new lines of road chiefly thro' Roscommon and</lb>
              Longford. This work, will not take up the whole</lb>
              
              of the summer, and as the Engineer is paid</lb>
              2 Gs. a mile, it will just support me till I</lb>
              have finished the drawing of Roscommon. Can you</lb>
              find out for me as [unclear]this[/unclear] young drawer, who would look</lb>
              forward like myself to good payment by his advance-</lb>
              -ment in life? All I want is a boy who can draw</lb>
              neat lines, I will give from 5 to 10 shillings a day.</lb>
              Now my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> let me thank you, and with just</lb>
                 The same feelings of Gratitude, as if we were first beginning</lb>
              work together. Thank you for the Fatherly determination</lb>
              with which you have managed my interests, and tho' I am</lb>
              not to be employed, I am convinced, that the manner in</lb>
              which you combined my employment, with yours, must</lb>
              have been of the highest service to me in London. And I</lb>
              have myself received proofs of a friendship, that I know not</lb>
              how I have earned but I hope I may</lb>
              always deserve to profess. </p> <closer>I am</lb>
Your most affectionate<lb/>
               W Edgeworth<lb/>
             
